definition.value: A diamine that is 1,2-phenylenediamine carrying a methyl substituent at position 4 and a 3-phenylpropyl substituent at position N1.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of amodiaquine; major species at pH 7.3.
A triazolobenzothiazole that is [1,2,4]triazolo[5,1-b][1,3]benzothiazole substituted at positions 1 and 2 by 4-methylbenzoyl and thioxo groups respectively.
An epoxide obtained by formal epoxidation across the 2,3-double bond of (6E)-2,6,11-trimethyldodeca-2,6,10-triene
A diol that is undecane in which a hydrogen attached to each of the terminal methyl groups has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A methanesulfonate salt obtained by reaction of tricaine with one molar equivalent of methanesulfonic acid. Used as an anaesthetic for fish.
A member of the class of oxadiazoles that is 1,2,3-oxadiazole carrying phenyl and thioxo substituents at positions 3 and 5 respectively.
A member of the class of dioxolanes that is 1,3-dioxolane substituted at position 2 by a sec-butyl group.
A member of the class of dioxolanes that is 1,3-dioxolane substituted at position 2 by a 6-heptynyl group.
A glycol that is (5Z,8Z)-1,5,8-undecatriene with the two hydroxy substituents located at positions 3 and 7.
A glycol that is (8E)-undeca-1,8-dien-5-yne with the two hydroxy substituents located at positions 3 and 7.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the anilino function of tricaine.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteine that is the thioester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of glyceric acid with the thiol group of N-acetyl-L-cysteine.
A monounsaturated fatty acid aldehyde that is undec-10-enal substituted at position 2 by a methyl group.
